Here is the code again:

const heading = React.createElement("h1", {}, "Hello world from react");

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(heading);

‚úÖ 1Ô∏è‚É£ React.createElement("h1", {}, "Hello world from react")

This is how React creates elements internally (without JSX).

It has 3 arguments:

React.createElement(type, props, children)


Breaking it down:

Argument	Meaning
"h1"	Type of element
{}	Props / attributes (none here)
"Hello world from react"	Child content (text)

So this line creates a virtual DOM object like:

{
  "type": "h1",
  "props": {
    "children": "Hello world from react"
  }
}


This is NOT an actual <h1> tag yet.
It‚Äôs just a JS object React uses internally.

JSX normally compiles to the same function.

For example:

<h1>Hello world from react</h1>


becomes:

React.createElement("h1", {}, "Hello world from react");


So here:

const heading = React.createElement(...);


stores that virtual element in heading.

‚úÖ 2Ô∏è‚É£ ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"))

This tells React where in the page to place the UI.

document.getElementById("root")

grabs:

<div id="root"></div>


Then:

ReactDOM.createRoot(...)


creates a root container for React 18‚Äôs concurrent renderer.

So this line means:

‚ÄúCreate a React application inside the div with id=root‚Äù

The returned object is stored in:

const root = ...

‚úÖ 3Ô∏è‚É£ root.render(heading)

This is where React actually updates the DOM.

heading is the virtual React element we created earlier.

React:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Takes the virtual DOM object
2Ô∏è‚É£ Converts it to real DOM
3Ô∏è‚É£ Inserts into <div id="root">

Result in browser:

<div id="root">
  <h1>Hello world from react</h1>
</div>

