üìò React Element Creation ‚Äî Theory & Key Concepts
‚úîÔ∏è What React.createElement() Does

React.createElement() is used to create React Elements

A React Element is not a real DOM node

It is a plain JavaScript object that represents:

element type

props / attributes

children

This object is part of the Virtual DOM tree

React uses these objects to understand:

what to render

what changed

what needs updating in the DOM

‚úîÔ∏è Structure of React.createElement(type, props, children)

type ‚Üí tag name or component name

props ‚Üí attributes / properties

children ‚Üí nested elements / text

Children can be:

a single value

an array of elements

Deeply nested elements are created
using nested React.createElement() calls

‚úîÔ∏è Output of React.createElement()

Returns a lightweight object

Example representation:

{
  type: "h1",
  props: {
    children: "Hello World"
  }
}


This object is part of the Virtual DOM

It is NOT yet inserted into the browser DOM

‚úîÔ∏è React vs Real DOM

React does not directly create DOM nodes

Instead it:

Creates React Elements (Virtual DOM objects)

Builds a Virtual DOM tree

Passes it to ReactDOM for rendering

‚úîÔ∏è When Real DOM Is Created

Real DOM nodes are created when we call:

root.render(element);


At this stage React:

Converts Virtual DOM ‚Üí Real DOM

Inserts elements into the browser

Applies updates efficiently

DOM updates are optimized using:

reconciliation

diffing algorithm

‚úîÔ∏è Why This Syntax Becomes Complex

Nested React.createElement() calls are:

verbose

hard to read

difficult to maintain

Large UI trees become complicated

Developer experience becomes poor

‚úîÔ∏è Why JSX Was Introduced

JSX is a syntactic sugar over React.createElement()

Provides HTML-like syntax

Easier to read and write

Improves developer productivity

JSX is not HTML ‚Äî it compiles to:

React.createElement() calls internally

‚úîÔ∏è Summary Points

React.createElement() creates React Elements

React Elements are Virtual DOM objects

They do not create real DOM nodes directly

Real DOM is created only during root.render()

React updates DOM efficiently using diffing

JSX exists to simplify writing UI structures

JSX and React.createElement() produce the same output


****************

‚úîÔ∏è What happens if <div id="root"> already has HTML inside it?

Example:

<div id="root">
  <h1>hello</h1>
</div>


When React executes:

root.render(element);


React will:

Take control of the #root container

Clear the existing DOM inside it

Replace it with React‚Äôs rendered content

So yes ‚Äî the previous content will be overwritten / replaced.

üß† Why React replaces existing content?

React assumes it fully owns the root container

Anything not created by React
may cause inconsistencies

So React removes existing nodes
and renders only its virtual DOM output

This ensures:

predictable rendering

consistent UI state

efficient updates afterward

‚úîÔ∏è Important Concept

React does not delete the <div id="root"> itself
It only replaces everything inside it.

So:

<div id="root">   <-- stays same
  (React content goes here)
</div>

‚ö†Ô∏è Best Practice

The #root div should be:

empty initially

dedicated only for React

Example:

<div id="root"></div>


Because mixing:

normal DOM content

React managed DOM content

is not recommended.

üéØ Summary (documentation-style)

React takes ownership of #root

Existing content inside root is removed

React renders its virtual DOM instead

Root container itself remains unchanged

React should be the only renderer inside root

so react takes full control of that root id div and clears anything exists puts the virtual dom element in it 
