üìò React ‚Äî Library vs Framework
‚úîÔ∏è React is a JavaScript Library

React is NOT a full framework

It focuses mainly on:

UI rendering

component-based architecture

state and UI updates

It does one job very well ‚Üí building user interfaces

React does not include:

routing

HTTP services

form validation

state management tools

build tooling

Those features come from separate libraries (React ecosystem).

Because of this, React is called:

A ‚Äúminimal‚Äù, ‚Äúlightweight‚Äù, or ‚ÄúUI library‚Äù.

‚úîÔ∏è JavaScript Framework (Example: Angular, Vue, Next.js)

A framework usually provides:

routing

HTTP / API utilities

state management

CLI & project structure

build + bundling system

dependency injection

form & validation utilities

testing tools

Frameworks tell you how the entire application must be structured.

React does NOT enforce this ‚Äî that‚Äôs why it‚Äôs a library.

üß† Where can React be used in a webpage?

React can run anywhere in the DOM, not only full pages.

You can mount React:

in header

in sidebar

in footer

inside a widget

inside only part of a page

Example:

<div id="header"></div>
<div id="sidebar"></div>
<div id="footer"></div>


You may render React into only one area:

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("sidebar"));
root.render(appComponent);


React does not require full-page control.

It can be embedded inside existing HTML.

‚úîÔ∏è Why React is flexible?

Because:

React works on a single root or multiple roots

Each root can be mounted independently

It can co-exist with normal JavaScript or jQuery

This is why React is popular for:

migrating legacy apps slowly

embedding widgets into dashboards

replacing parts of UI step-by-step

üéØ Final Summary (Short Points)

React is a UI library, not a framework

It focuses only on view + rendering

Other features come from external packages

React can render:

full applications OR

small parts of a webpage

It can run in header, footer, sidebar, or anywhere in DOM


 